EXPERIMENT: D9_DISSOCIATION_STAT3_GBM_v1
DATE: 2026-06-06
STATUS: pre-registered
DATASET: PRISM Repurposing 20Q2 Secondary Screen
EXTENDS: D8_CROSS_CANCER_REPURPOSING_v1 (pre-reg 03b1d21)

MOTIVATION:
D8 established two cases for the structural pharmacology boundary condition:
  - MEK1 in BRAF-MEL: structural anchor + driver-pathway → kills (D8 H1 ✓)
  - CDK4 in PDAC: structural SIGNIFICANT + NOT driver-pathway → does NOT kill (D8 H3 ✗)

These two cases are consistent with the boundary condition:
  "Structural position predicts lethality only when target is
   co-pathway with the DEPENDENCY-DRIVER of the cancer."

D9 tests a THIRD case designed to discriminate between two refinements:

REFINEMENT A (strict): Target must be the DEPENDENCY-DRIVER itself or
  directly activated by it (CDK4 in PDAC = NOT dependency-driver → fails)
REFINEMENT B (loose): Target must be on a signaling pathway the cancer
  DEPENDS ON (indirect pathway activation is sufficient)

TEST CASE: STAT3 in GBM
  STAT3 z_dr in GBM: robust ANCHOR (z1=−1.12, z2=−1.20) [from D7]
  STAT3 in GBM biology: activated DOWNSTREAM of EGFR (EGFR → JAK2 → STAT3)
    STAT3 is NOT the primary GBM driver (EGFR/PTEN/IDH1 drive GBM)
    But STAT3 IS activated in GBM via the EGFR pathway → indirect co-pathway
  Under Refinement A: STAT3 should NOT predict lethality (not driver-pathway)
  Under Refinement B: STAT3 SHOULD predict lethality (activated by EGFR pathway)
  → D9 H1 outcome determines which refinement holds

SECONDARY TEST CASE: PI3K inhibitors in CRC
  PI3K z_dr in CRC: robust ANCHOR (z1=−1.31, z2=−1.15) [from D7]
  PI3K in CRC biology: KRAS → PI3K (direct pathway, KRAS activates PI3K)
    PI3K IS co-pathway with KRAS, but KRAS-mutant CRC is resistant to
    PI3K inhibitors clinically (feedback reactivation through MEK)
  → Tests if structural position predicts despite known clinical resistance

CONTROL TEST: MEK inhibitors in GBM vs melanoma (replicate D8 in new context)
  MEK1 z_dr in GBM:      z1=+1.49, z2=+0.91 (consistent DAMPER — not robust)
  MEK1 z_dr in BRAF-MEL: z1=−1.10, z2=−1.45 (robust ANCHOR)
  Prediction: MEK inhibitors kill BRAF-MEL more than GBM (D8 replicate)
  If confirmed: consistent with D8 and structural model
  If denied: regime classification of MEK1 in GBM needs revision

PRIMARY HYPOTHESIS (H1, CONFIRMATORY):
STAT3 inhibitors (napabucasin, niclosamide, WP1066, stattic) show
significantly more negative mean LFC in GBM/glioma cell lines
(primary_tissue='central_nervous_system', secondary_tissue='glioma', n=85)
than in CRC cell lines (primary_tissue='colorectal', n=46).

STAT3 z_dr in GBM = robust ANCHOR (structural prediction: kills GBM)
STAT3 NOT in CRC network / near-neutral in most non-GBM contexts
Statistical test: Mann-Whitney U (GBM < CRC), p < 0.05

H1 confirmed → Refinement B holds: indirect co-pathway activation
  sufficient for structural prediction; boundary condition is looser
  than D8 H3 suggested
H1 denied → Refinement A may hold: only dependency-driver co-pathway
  proteins are predictable by structural position

SECONDARY HYPOTHESIS (H2, CONFIRMATORY):
PI3K inhibitors show significantly more negative LFC in CRC than
in melanoma (secondary_tissue='melanoma', n=45).
PI3K z_dr in CRC: robust ANCHOR (z1=−1.31, z2=−1.15)
PI3K z_dr in BRAF-MEL: z1=+1.21, z2=+0.63 (consistent DAMPER — not robust)
Structural prediction: PI3K inhibition kills CRC (anchor destabilization)
  less so in BRAF-MEL (PI3K is a damper there)
Note: PI3K inhibitors clinically resistant in KRAS-CRC — a negative result
  here would align clinical resistance with structural model (damper relief
  in ODS = mild effect; but PI3K is an ANCHOR in CRC so this should kill)
  WAIT: PI3K is ANCHOR in CRC under z_dr correction → structural prediction
  IS that PI3K inhibitors kill CRC. Clinical resistance may be a feedback
  phenomenon not captured in short-term PRISM viability assay.

EXPLORATORY (H3): MEK inhibitors in GBM vs BRAF-MEL
  Replication of D8 pattern: MEK inhibitors should kill BRAF-MEL > GBM
  MEK1 z_dr: robust ANCHOR in BRAF-MEL vs consistent DAMPER in GBM
  If H3 confirmed: structural regime-switch replicates in second independent comparison

CELL LINES (confirmed from PRISM metadata before LFC access):
  GBM (glioma): n=85  (primary_tissue='central_nervous_system',
                        secondary_tissue='glioma')
  CRC: n=38 (from PRISM, as in D8)
  Melanoma: n=45 (from PRISM, as in D8)
  Lung NSC: n~191 (comparison for extended analysis)

DRUGS:
  STAT3 inhibitors: napabucasin (24 PRISM entries), niclosamide (8),
                    WP1066 (8), stattic (8)
  PI3K inhibitors: copanlisib, buparlisib, alpelisib, idelalisib, GDC-0941
  MEK inhibitors (H3): trametinib, cobimetinib, selumetinib (as in D8)

BOUNDARY CONDITION INTERPRETATION TABLE:
  Case              | z_dr signal | Co-pathway? | Prediction | Prior result
  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  MEK1/BRAF-MEL     | robust ANCHOR | yes (direct) | kill      | D8 H1 ✓
  CDK4/PDAC         | SIGNIFICANT   | no           | no kill   | D8 H3 ✓
  STAT3/GBM         | robust ANCHOR | indirect     | ?         | D9 H1 TBD
  PI3K/CRC          | robust ANCHOR | yes (direct) | kill      | D9 H2 TBD

DECISION RULE:
H1 confirmed + H2 confirmed → boundary: "any activated pathway member"
H1 denied   + H2 confirmed → boundary: "direct driver co-pathway only"
H1 confirmed + H2 denied   → anomaly; resistance mechanisms override structure
Both denied → structural model limited to direct dependency-driver targets
